{
    "publish_date": "2014-03-10T15:08:46.000Z", 
    "video_length": "PT3M55S", 
    "captions": [
        {
            "text": "Why does your mouth feel like it&#39;s on fire", 
            "dur": "2", 
            "start": "6.951"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "when you eat a spicy pepper?", 
            "dur": "1.963", 
            "start": "8.951"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And how do you soothe the burn?", 
            "dur": "1.869", 
            "start": "10.914"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Why does wasabi make your eyes water?", 
            "dur": "2.053", 
            "start": "12.783"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And how spicy is the spiciest spice?", 
            "dur": "3.447", 
            "start": "14.836"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Let&#39;s back up a bit.", 
            "dur": "1.083", 
            "start": "18.283"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "First, what is spiciness?", 
            "dur": "2.436", 
            "start": "19.366"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Even though we often say that something tastes spicy,", 
            "dur": "3.013", 
            "start": "21.802"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "it&#39;s not actually a taste,", 
            "dur": "1.782", 
            "start": "24.815"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "like sweet or salty or sour.", 
            "dur": "2.254", 
            "start": "26.597"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Instead, what&#39;s really happening", 
            "dur": "1.291", 
            "start": "28.851"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "is that certain compounds in spicy foods", 
            "dur": "1.836", 
            "start": "30.142"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "activate the type of sensory neurons", 
            "dur": "1.833", 
            "start": "31.978"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "called polymodal nociceptors.", 
            "dur": "3.05", 
            "start": "33.811"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You have these all over your body,", 
            "dur": "1.709", 
            "start": "36.861"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "including your mouth and nose,", 
            "dur": "1.897", 
            "start": "38.57"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and they&#39;re the same receptors", 
            "dur": "1.51", 
            "start": "40.467"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that are activated by extreme heat.", 
            "dur": "2.346", 
            "start": "41.977"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So, when you eat a chili pepper,", 
            "dur": "1.457", 
            "start": "44.323"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "your mouth feels like it&#39;s burning", 
            "dur": "1.668", 
            "start": "45.78"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "because your brain actually thinks it&#39;s burning.", 
            "dur": "2.881", 
            "start": "47.448"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The opposite happens when you eat something", 
            "dur": "1.583", 
            "start": "50.329"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "with menthol in it.", 
            "dur": "1.505", 
            "start": "51.912"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The cool, minty compound", 
            "dur": "1.278", 
            "start": "53.417"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "is activating your cold receptors.", 
            "dur": "2.252", 
            "start": "54.695"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "When these heat-sensitive receptors are activated,", 
            "dur": "1.85", 
            "start": "56.947"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "your body thinks it&#39;s in contact", 
            "dur": "1.503", 
            "start": "58.797"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "with a dangerous heat source", 
            "dur": "1.333", 
            "start": "60.3"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and reacts accordingly.", 
            "dur": "1.396", 
            "start": "61.633"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "This is why you start to sweat,", 
            "dur": "1.482", 
            "start": "63.029"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and your heart starts beating faster.", 
            "dur": "1.667", 
            "start": "64.511"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The peppers have elicited", 
            "dur": "1.212", 
            "start": "66.178"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the same fight-or-flight response", 
            "dur": "1.376", 
            "start": "67.39"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "with which your body reacts to most threats.", 
            "dur": "2.418", 
            "start": "68.766"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But you may have noticed that", 
            "dur": "1.356", 
            "start": "71.184"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "not all spicy foods are spicy in the same way.", 
            "dur": "2.857", 
            "start": "72.54"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And the difference lies in the types of compounds involved.", 
            "dur": "3.131", 
            "start": "75.397"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The capsaicin and piperine,", 
            "dur": "1.706", 
            "start": "78.528"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "found in black pepper and chili peppers,", 
            "dur": "1.752", 
            "start": "80.234"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "are made up of larger, heavier molecules", 
            "dur": "2.001", 
            "start": "81.986"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "called alkylamides,", 
            "dur": "1.67", 
            "start": "83.987"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and those mostly stay in your mouth.", 
            "dur": "1.918", 
            "start": "85.657"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Mustard, horseradish, and wasabi", 
            "dur": "2.002", 
            "start": "87.575"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "are made up of smaller molecules,", 
            "dur": "1.702", 
            "start": "89.577"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "called isothiocyanates,", 
            "dur": "2.25", 
            "start": "91.279"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that easily float up into your sinuses.", 
            "dur": "2.75", 
            "start": "93.529"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "This is why chili peppers burn your mouth,", 
            "dur": "2.083", 
            "start": "96.279"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and wasabi burns your nose.", 
            "dur": "3.085", 
            "start": "98.362"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The standard measure of a food&#39;s spiciness", 
            "dur": "1.52", 
            "start": "101.447"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "is its rating on the Scoville scale,", 
            "dur": "1.749", 
            "start": "102.967"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "which measures how much its capsaicin content can be diluted", 
            "dur": "3.238", 
            "start": "104.716"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "before the heat is no longer detectable to humans.", 
            "dur": "2.603", 
            "start": "107.954"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "A sweet bell pepper gets 0 Scoville heat units,", 
            "dur": "2.627", 
            "start": "110.557"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "while Tabasco sauce clocks in between 1,200-2,400 units.", 
            "dur": "4.679", 
            "start": "113.184"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The race to create the hottest pepper", 
            "dur": "1.537", 
            "start": "117.863"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "is a constant battle,", 
            "dur": "1.461", 
            "start": "119.4"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but two peppers generally come out on top:", 
            "dur": "2.124", 
            "start": "120.861"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The Trinidad Moruga Scorpion", 
            "dur": "2.086", 
            "start": "122.985"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and the Carolina Reaper.", 
            "dur": "1.669", 
            "start": "125.071"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "These peppers measure", 
            "dur": "1.372", 
            "start": "126.74"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "between 1.5 and 2 million Scoville heat units,", 
            "dur": "2.881", 
            "start": "128.112"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "which is about half the units found in pepper spray.", 
            "dur": "3.702", 
            "start": "130.993"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So, why would anyone want to eat something", 
            "dur": "1.751", 
            "start": "134.695"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that causes such high levels of pain?", 
            "dur": "2.75", 
            "start": "136.446"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Nobody really knows when or why", 
            "dur": "1.974", 
            "start": "139.196"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "humans started eating hot peppers.", 
            "dur": "2.044", 
            "start": "141.17"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Archaeologists have found spices like mustard", 
            "dur": "2.085", 
            "start": "143.214"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "along with human artifacts", 
            "dur": "1.878", 
            "start": "145.299"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "dating as far back as 23,000 years ago.", 
            "dur": "1.876", 
            "start": "147.177"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But they don&#39;t know whether the spices were used", 
            "dur": "1.751", 
            "start": "149.053"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "for food or medication or just decoration.", 
            "dur": "3.225", 
            "start": "150.804"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "More recently, a 6,000 year old crockpot,", 
            "dur": "1.781", 
            "start": "154.029"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "lined with charred fish and meat,", 
            "dur": "2.052", 
            "start": "155.81"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "also contained mustard.", 
            "dur": "1.66", 
            "start": "157.862"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "One theory says that humans", 
            "dur": "1.626", 
            "start": "159.522"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "starting adding spices to food", 
            "dur": "1.252", 
            "start": "161.148"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to kill off bacteria.", 
            "dur": "1.544", 
            "start": "162.4"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And some studies show that spice developed", 
            "dur": "2.254", 
            "start": "163.944"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "mostly in warmer climates", 
            "dur": "1.414", 
            "start": "166.198"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "where microbes also happen to be more prevalent.", 
            "dur": "2.667", 
            "start": "167.612"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But why we continue to subject ourselves", 
            "dur": "2.417", 
            "start": "170.279"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to spicy food today", 
            "dur": "1.251", 
            "start": "172.696"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "is still a bit of a mystery.", 
            "dur": "1.665", 
            "start": "173.947"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "For some people,", 
            "dur": "1.007", 
            "start": "175.612"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "eating spicy food", 
            "dur": "1.077", 
            "start": "176.619"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "is like riding rollercoasters;", 
            "dur": "1.221", 
            "start": "177.696"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "they enjoy the ensuing thrill,", 
            "dur": "1.529", 
            "start": "178.917"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "even if the immediate sensation is unpleasant.", 
            "dur": "3", 
            "start": "180.446"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Some studies have even shown", 
            "dur": "1.31", 
            "start": "183.446"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that those who like to eat hot stuff", 
            "dur": "1.459", 
            "start": "184.756"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "are more likely to enjoy other adrenaline-rich activities,", 
            "dur": "2.711", 
            "start": "186.215"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "like gambling.", 
            "dur": "1.628", 
            "start": "188.926"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The taste for spicy food", 
            "dur": "1.415", 
            "start": "190.554"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "may even be genetic.", 
            "dur": "1.629", 
            "start": "191.969"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And if you&#39;re thinking about training a bit,", 
            "dur": "1.96", 
            "start": "193.598"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to up your tolerance for spice,", 
            "dur": "1.501", 
            "start": "195.558"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "know this:", 
            "dur": "1.053", 
            "start": "197.059"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "According to some studies,", 
            "dur": "1.284", 
            "start": "198.112"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the pain doesn&#39;t get any better.", 
            "dur": "1.835", 
            "start": "199.396"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You just get tougher.", 
            "dur": "1.715", 
            "start": "201.231"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "In fact, researchers have found", 
            "dur": "1.666", 
            "start": "202.946"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that people who like to eat spicy foods", 
            "dur": "1.833", 
            "start": "204.612"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "don&#39;t rate the burn any less painful", 
            "dur": "2.584", 
            "start": "206.445"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "than those who don&#39;t.", 
            "dur": "1.583", 
            "start": "209.029"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "They just seem to like the pain more.", 
            "dur": "2.751", 
            "start": "210.612"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So, torment your heat receptors all you want,", 
            "dur": "1.748", 
            "start": "213.363"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but remember, when it comes to spicy food,", 
            "dur": "2.302", 
            "start": "215.111"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you&#39;re going to get burned.", 
            "dur": "1.616", 
            "start": "217.413"
        }
    ], 
